<br>
As far as the Catholic vs. Christian thing goes...I personally do not care what a collection of people visiting a web page has to say.  Catholics are Christians.  Not only do the members consider themselves such, but even the priests refer to their faith as &quot;Christianity&quot; during the course of his sermons.  I have been a member of the Catholic church and during that time I always considered myself of the Christian faith, just as one of the many, many branches of Christianity.  &quot;Christians&quot;, as they'd have it can argue that Catholics aren not Christians all they want if that makes them feel special and different.<br>
<br>
On the same note, it doesn't really matter in this situation.  Both believe in God.  Hell, if there was a religion that encourages their members to do the exact opposite of what Christians, Catholics, etc. believed, but still called their deity &quot;God&quot;, they'd fall under the same category in this discussion, because the words &quot;under God&quot; refer to their belief.<br>
<br>
I find it amazing on how one letter can change so much.  I wanted to argue that &quot;God&quot; refers to the spirit(s) that protect our lands, as others have.  Unfortunately, I don't think I can do that.  To me, the terms &quot;god&quot; and &quot;God&quot; are different, where one is referring to an essence and another is referring to a name.  The fact that this single word is capitalized does give the people against this line some ground to argue from in my eyes.<br>
<br>
I don't believe that children as as impressionable as the people here claim, however.  I know that when I was in school, the line &quot;under God&quot; never made me think about God, or that there had to be one because these words we say in the mornings provide irrefutable proof that there is a divine spirit watching over me.  If it did, I would have believed in God from the other 10,000 references to Him a child hears in a day.<br>
<br>
For myself, I would like to see the pledge remain how it was, but I wouldn't lose any sleep were it changed.  The main reason I would like to see the decision overruled is security.  What will someone find next they don't like and demand that it be changed as well?  If the Pledge of Allegience is changed, what's next?<br>
<br>
